  "prompt": "What books should every teenager read?",
  "response": "Every teenager should consider reading the following books, as they are popular choices that explore various themes relevant to their age group. These books can provide valuable lessons, entertainment, and a broader perspective on life:\n\n1. **To Kill a Mockingbird** by Harper Lee\n   - Explores themes of racism and prejudice through the eyes of a young girl in the American South.\n\n2. **The Catcher in the Rye** by J.D. Salinger\n   - A classic coming-of-age story that delves into teenage angst and the search for identity.\n\n3. **The Diary of a Young Girl** by Anne Frank\n   - A poignant firsthand account of a Jewish girl's experiences during the Holocaust.\n\n4. **Lord of the Flies** by William Golding\n   - A thought-provoking novel about the dark side of human nature and the struggle for civilization.\n\n5. **The Outsiders** by S.E. Hinton\n   - A powerful story about class conflict, friendship, and the complexities of growing up.\n\n6. **The Perks of Being a Wallflower** by Stephen Chbosky\n   - A novel that addresses issues such as mental health, friendship, and coming of age.\n\n7. **The Hunger Games** by Suzanne Collins\n   - A gripping dystopian novel that tackles themes of power, resistance, and survival.\n\n8. **1984** by George Orwell\n   - A cautionary tale about totalitarianism, surveillance, and the power of language.\n\n9. **Little Women** by Louisa May Alcott\n   - A timeless story about the joys and challenges of family life and personal growth.\n\n10. **The Fault in Our Stars** by John Green\n    - A heart-wrenching yet uplifting novel about love, life, and coping with terminal illness.\n\nThese books cover a range of genres and themes, offering teenagers valuable insights into various aspects of life, society, and human nature.",
